What is the structure of your dataset?¶

We have 174952 row data set for Bike-Share aystem at San Francisco pay area has data about noumber seconds of bike using, the start and end time of using bike, the start station and end station of using bike, aslo information about users (birth year, gender, Subscriber or not)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in figuring out the distribution of time spent using bike 24/7 and which age group prefer bike share

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Duration in seconds and End Time will be the main feature as it the way we use to measure the time spent and its pattern

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Distributions of duration

  • The duration in seconds took on a large range of values, so I looked at the data using a log transform Under the transformation, the data looked unimodal, with one peak between 5 and 15 minutes

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

>

  • The birth year of some subscribers not logical (birth year 1878 means that subscriber is 141 old), so we remove all subscribers above 80 old as we suspect that it's false data as bike is not safe for aging people.
  • The main idea of bike share is using bike to move inside city fast from point to point not keeping bike with customer for long time or next day, so we slecte the max period of bike usage is 45 minutes and remove dataset whcih exceed that limit.

def tick_count_covert(x):
    '''Convert the Y ticks count of trips to be in thousands '''
    labels = []
    for i in x:
        labels.append(str(int(i/1000))+'K')
    return labels
In [47]:
def tick_seconds_covert(x):
    '''Convert the Y ticks from seconds to be in minutes '''
    labels = []
    for i in x:
        labels.append(str(int(i/60)))
    return labels

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)
